\textbf{Analysis of Efficiency.}\;
We compare
\[
    4n^{2},\quad \log_3 n,\quad 3^{n},\quad 20n,\quad 2,\quad \log_2 n,\quad n^{2/3}
\]
to determine which yields the smallest value for each integer~$n$.

\begin{itemize}

    \item \textbf{At $n=1$:}\;
          $\log_2 1 = \log_3 1 = 0$, smaller than every other expression.
          The logarithmic functions are most efficient here.

    \item \textbf{For $2 \le n \le 8$:}\;
          $\log_3 n$ grows more slowly than $\log_2 n$ and remains below
          all other functions.  At $n=8$, $\log_3 8 \approx 1.89 < 2$.

    \item \textbf{For $n \ge 9$:}\;
          $\log_3 9 = 2$, so from here the constant function~$2$ ties and
          then beats $\log_3 n$.  The constant~$2$ is most efficient.

\end{itemize}

\medskip
\textbf{Conclusion:}
\begin{itemize}
    \item $\log_2 n$ and $\log_3 n$ are most efficient at $n=1$.
    \item $\log_3 n$ is most efficient for $2 \le n \le 8$.
    \item The constant $2$ is most efficient for $n \ge 9$.
\end{itemize}

\smallskip
\textit{Remark.}\;
The functions $4n^{2}$, $3^{n}$, $20n$, and $n^{2/3}$ are never the
most efficient for any integer $n \ge 1$.





